<dl id="n05156d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05156d">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05156d"> 156(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> &lsquo;Amen&rsquo; says the Lia Fail / (Stone) <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n05156d"><li>FW 558.20 </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/lexs.htm#n05156d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/s/l39s.htm#n05156d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n05156d">MS BL 47482a-42v</ms> </li><li>JJA 60:138 <a name="sb0d" href="../../ff/fdra/sda.htm#sD0d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/s/sd0d.htm#n05156d">Draft: III&sect;4D.0</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The last wonder described by Dr. Joyce is the <mark>Lia Fail, or Coronation Stone of Tara</mark>, on which the ancient kings of Ireland were crowned and &ldquo;which uttered a shout whenever a king of the true Scotic or Irish race stood or sat on it.&rdquo; <small> Alfred Perceval Graves, <a name="ILMS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ILMS"><cite title="source">Irish Literary and Musical Studies</cite></a>, (1913) [Dr. Joyce&apos;s Irish Wonder Book] 172</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
